riting init container script... keystore-vol` as an emptyDir volume, then mount it in the main container so the updated keystore persists. I'm refining the approach to copy the base keystore to a working directory, set `ES_PATH_CONF` to point there, add the credentials, and then access the modified keystore through the volume mount.\n\nI'm also verifying that `ES_PATH_CONF` correctly redirects the keystore location and checking whether the `--force` flag is appropriate for adding credentials to a fresh, unprotected keystore. I'm wondering whether the Elasticsearch Docker container does anything special with an existing keystore when it starts up, or if it just reads it as-is. The entrypoint script typically creates a fresh keystore if one doesn't exist, but since I'm mounting a pre-created keystore via subPath, it should use that instead. I need to verify the exact behavior of the `--force` flag in ES 7.17.9 when adding keystore entries.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the elasticsearch.yml configuration more carefully for S3/MinIO integration. The S3 repository plugin uses named clients, and the default client settings need to be prefixed with `s3.client.default.*` in the YAML file, but I should double-check the exact property names to make sure they're correct. need to verify whether `path_style_access` can also be set at the client level in elasticsearch.yml, since the docs seem to suggest it's only a repository-level setting. For MinIO specifically, I'd configure the endpoint and protocol in elasticsearch.yml, then set `path_style_access: true` when registering the repository through the API. I'm settling on keeping `disable_chunked_encoding` simple for now and only adding it if issues arise. My final configuration includes the MinIO endpoint with port and HTTP protocol in the Elasticsearch settings, then the repository registration with path-style access enabled and the default client specified. I'll also need to configure the secure keystore settings for the access credentials.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the StatefulSet patch for the init containers—patching the statefulset will trigger a rolling restart of the pods one at a time, which is necessary for the plugin installation. I need to be careful about the user context for the keystore command since Elasticsearch runs as the `elasticsearch` user, so the init container should ideally run with the same permissions.\n\nMy plan is to add two volumes (one for the S3 plugin staging and one for the keystore) and then set up init containers that install the S3 plugin and handle the keystore setup, making sure the files are accessible to the Elasticsearch user.\n\nSetting up init containers... Writing init container config... Adding keystore credentials...\n\nThe approach is to modify the keystore directly in the init container's own filesystem at the standard location, then copy the updated keystore to the shared volume for the main container to use. I'm realizing the `--force` flag might not be necessary since we're adding new entries to a fresh keystore each time, but I should verify whether these entries already exist or if they need to be overwritten. I'll copy the keystore to the shared volume after modifying it in the init container, which keeps things clean. I should also verify that permissions are preserved when copying—the keystore needs to be readable by the elasticsearch user. The init container will need network access for the plugin installation, which could take some time. For patching the StatefulSet, I'm considering using a strategic merge patch to add the new volumes, init containers, and volume mounts.\n\nDefining the patch structure... I'm double-checking the Elasticsearch 7.x repository-s3 plugin documentation to clarify which settings are client-level versus repository-level, since `path_style_access` might belong in either place depending on the version. and the repository registration just needs the bucket name, though I should verify whether `path_style_access` belongs at the client level or repository level—the documentation suggests it's a client-level setting, but I've seen it referenced both ways, so I might need to configure it in both places to be safe. I'm storing the S3 credentials in a Kubernetes secret with the proper keystore naming convention, then I'll register the repository with the bucket and path style access settings configured.\n\nNow I'm thinking through whether chunked encoding needs to be disabled for MinIO compatibility—since we're using a recent MinIO version, it should handle chunked uploads fine, so I can skip that setting.\n\nLet me map out the full execution sequence: create the MinIO service, set up the secure settings secret, update the Elasticsearch configuration, create the backups bucket, patch the StatefulSet to trigger a rolling restart, verify all pods are ready, then register the snapshot repository and test it.\n\nI should also be careful with how I pass the access key to the keystore command—using `printf` or a heredoc might be safer than `echo` to ensure the newline handling is correct for the keystore add operation.\n\nLet me try a simpler approach: run the keystore commands directly in the init container using its default config directory, then copy the resulting keystore file to the shared volume so the main container can use it. I'm concerned though that the keystore might not exist in a fresh init container instance, so I need to check how the Elasticsearch Docker image handles keystore initialization. Finishing the copy command to move the keystore to the staging directory. Looking at the actual keystore contents from the running cluster, it already has the seed and S3 credentials, which suggests either a custom image or some initialization process I'm not seeing. Let me investigate what's actually populating that keystore during cluster startup.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_